# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antibody-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] An **antibody** (**Ab**), or **immunoglobulin** (**Ig**), is a large protein belonging to the immunoglobulin superfamily which is used by the immune system to identify and neutralize antigens such as those that exist on bacteria and virus cells, including those that cause disease.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Each individual antibody recognizes one or more specific antigens, and antigens (a portmanteau of "antibody generator") of virtually any size and chemical composition can be recognized.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Each of the branching chains comprising the "Y" of an antibody contains a paratope (the antigen-binding site) that specifically binds to one particular epitope (a specific part of an antigen bound by the paratope) on an antigen, allowing the two molecules to bind together with precision.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Using this mechanism, antibodies can effectively "tag" the antigen (or a microbe or an infected cell bearing such an antigen) for attack by cells of the immune system, or can neutralize it directly (for example, by blocking a part of a virus that is essential for its ability to invade a host cell).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies may be borne on the surface of an immune cell, as in a B cell receptor, or they may exist freely by being secreted into the extracellular space.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The term *antibody* generally refers to the free (secreted) form, while the term *immunoglobulin* can refer to either forms.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Since they are, broadly speaking, the same protein, the terms are often treated as synonymous.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] To allow the immune system to recognize millions of different antigens, the antigen-binding paratopes at each tip of the antibody come in an equally wide variety.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The rest of an antibody's structure is much less variable; in humans, antibodies occur in five classes or isotypes: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Human IgG and IgA antibodies are also divided into discrete subclasses (IgG1, IgG2, IgG3, and IgG4; IgA1 and IgA2).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The class refers to the functions triggered by the antibody (also known as effector functions), in addition to some other structural features.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies from different classes also differ in where they are released in the body and at what stage of an immune response.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Between species, while classes and subclasses of antibodies may be shared (at least in name), their function and distribution throughout the body may be different, which complicates the use of animal models in studying antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] For example, mouse IgG1 is closer to human IgG2 than to human IgG1 in terms of its function.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In general, antibodies are considered part of the adaptive immune system, though this classification can become complicated.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] For example, natural IgM, which are made by B-1 cells that have properties more similar to innate immune cells than adaptive, refers to IgM antibodies made independently of an immune response that demonstrate polyreactivity—i.e. they recognize multiple distinct (unrelated) antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These can work with the complement system in the earliest phases of an immune response to help facilitate clearance of the offending antigen and delivery of the resulting immune complexes to the lymph nodes or spleen for initiation of an immune response.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Hence in this capacity, the functions of antibodies are more akin to that of innate immunity than adaptive.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies arise from antibody-secreting cells, a term that encompasses plasmablasts and plasma cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In the course of an immune response, B cells can progressively differentiate into antibody-secreting cells or into memory B cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Plasmablasts and plasma cells differ mainly in the degree to which they secrete antibodies, their lifespan, metabolic adaptations, and surface markers.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Plasmablasts are rapidly proliferating, short-lived cells produced in the early phases of the immune response (classically described as arising from extrafollicular reactions rather than from a germinal center) which have the potential to differentiate further into plasma cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Occasionally plasmablasts are mis-described as short-lived plasma cells; formally this is incorrect because plasma cells do not divide (they are terminally differentiated), and rely on survival niches comprising specific cell types and cytokines to persist.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] It is commonly said that plasma cells do not express surface immunoglobulin (whereas plasmablasts do), but this depends on the class of antibody that the plasma cell generates (IgG-secreting plasma cells do not, but IgM, IgA, and IgE plasma cells do).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Plasma cells will secrete huge quantities of antibody regardless of whether or not antigen is present, ensuring that antibody levels to the antigen in question do not fall to zero, provided the plasma cell stays alive.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The rate of antibody secretion, however, can be regulated, for example, by the presence of adjuvant molecules that stimulate the immune response such as toll-like receptor ligands.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Long-lived plasma cells can live for potentially the entire lifetime of the organism.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Classically, the survival niches that house long-lived plasma cells reside in the bone marrow, though it cannot be assumed that any given plasma cell in the bone marrow will be long-lived.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] However, other work indicates that survival niches can readily be established within the mucosal tissues, though the classes of antibodies involved show a different hierarchy from those in the bone marrow.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] B cells can also differentiate into memory B cells which can persist for decades, similarly to long-lived plasma cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These cells can be rapidly recalled in a secondary immune response, undergoing class switching, affinity maturation, and differentiating into antibody-secreting cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies are heavy (~150 kDa) proteins of about 10 nm in size, arranged in three globular regions that roughly form a Y shape.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In humans and most other mammals, an antibody unit consists of four polypeptide chains; two identical *heavy chains* and two identical *light chains* connected by disulfide bonds.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Each chain is a series of domains: somewhat similar sequences of about 110 amino acids each.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These domains are usually represented in simplified schematics as rectangles.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Light chains consist of one variable domain VL and one constant domain CL, while heavy chains contain one variable domain VH and three to four constant domains CH1, CH2, ...
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Structurally an antibody is also partitioned into two antigen-binding fragments (Fab), containing one VL, VH, CL, and CH1 domain each, as well as the crystallisable fragment (Fc), forming the trunk of the Y shape.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In between them is a hinge region of the heavy chains, whose flexibility allows antibodies to bind to pairs of epitopes at various distances, to form complexes (dimers, trimers, etc.), and to bind effector molecules more easily.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In an electrophoresis test of blood proteins, antibodies mostly migrate to the last, gamma globulin fraction.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Conversely, most gamma-globulins are antibodies, which is why the two terms were historically used as synonyms, as were the symbols Ig and γ.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This variant terminology fell out of use due to the correspondence being inexact and due to confusion with γ (gamma) heavy chains which characterize the IgG class of antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The variable domains can also be referred to as the FV region.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] It is the subregion of Fab that binds to an antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] More specifically, each variable domain contains three *hypervariable regions* – the amino acids seen there vary the most from antibody to antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] When the protein folds, these regions give rise to three loops of β-strands, localized near one another on the surface of the antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These loops are referred to as the complementarity-determining regions (CDRs), since their shape complements that of an antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Three CDRs from each of the heavy and light chains together form an antibody-binding site whose shape can be anything from a pocket to which a smaller antigen binds, to a larger surface, to a protrusion that sticks out into a groove in an antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Typically though, only a few residues contribute to most of the binding energy.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The structures of CDRs have been clustered and classified by Chothia et al. and more recently by North et al. and Nikoloudis et al.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] However, describing an antibody's binding site using only one single static structure limits the understanding and characterization of the antibody's function and properties.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] To improve antibody structure prediction and to take the strongly correlated CDR loop and interface movements into account, antibody paratopes should be described as interconverting states in solution with varying probabilities.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In the framework of the immune network theory, CDRs are also called idiotypes.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] According to immune network theory, the adaptive immune system is regulated by interactions between idiotypes.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The Fc region (the trunk of the Y shape) is composed of constant domains from the heavy chains.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Its role is in modulating immune cell activity: it is where effector molecules bind to, triggering various effects after the antibody Fab region binds to an antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Effector cells (such as macrophages or natural killer cells) bind via their Fc receptors (FcR) to the Fc region of an antibody, while the complement system is activated by binding the C1q protein complex (also via the Fc region).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] IgG or IgM can bind to C1q, but IgA cannot, therefore IgA does not activate the classical complement pathway.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Another role of the Fc region is to selectively distribute different antibody classes across the body.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In particular, the neonatal Fc receptor (FcRn) binds to the Fc region of IgG antibodies to transport it across the placenta, from the mother to the fetus.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In addition to this, binding to FcRn endows IgG with an exceptionally long half-life relative to other plasma proteins of 3–4 weeks.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] IgG3 in most cases (depending on allotype) has mutations at the FcRn binding site which lower affinity for FcRn, which are thought to have evolved to limit the highly inflammatory effects of this subclass.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies are glycoproteins, that is, they have carbohydrates (glycans) added to conserved amino acid residues.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These conserved glycosylation sites occur in the Fc region and influence interactions with effector molecules.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The N-terminus of each chain is situated at the tip.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Each immunoglobulin domain has a similar structure, characteristic of all the members of the immunoglobulin superfamily: it is composed of between 7 (for constant domains) and 9 (for variable domains) β-strands, forming two beta sheets in a Greek key motif.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The sheets create a "sandwich" shape, the immunoglobulin fold, held together by a disulfide bond.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Secreted antibodies can occur as a single Y-shaped unit, a monomer.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] However, some antibody classes also form dimers with two Ig units (as with IgA), tetramers with four Ig units (like teleost fish IgM), or pentamers with five Ig units (like shark IgW or mammalian IgM, which occasionally forms hexamers as well, with six units).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] IgG can also form hexamers, though no J chain is required.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] IgA tetramers and pentamers have also been reported.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies also form complexes by binding to antigen: this is called an antigen-antibody complex or *immune complex*.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Small antigens can cross-link two antibodies, also leading to the formation of antibody dimers, trimers, tetramers, etc.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Multivalent antigens (e.g., cells with multiple epitopes) can form larger complexes with antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] An extreme example is the clumping, or agglutination, of red blood cells with antibodies in blood typing to determine blood groups: the large clumps become insoluble, leading to visually apparent precipitation.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The membrane-bound form of an antibody may be called a *surface immunoglobulin* (sIg) or a *membrane immunoglobulin* (mIg).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] It is part of the *B cell receptor* (BCR), which allows a B cell to detect when a specific antigen is present in the body and triggers B cell activation.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The BCR is composed of surface-bound IgD or IgM antibodies and associated Ig-α and Ig-β heterodimers, which are capable of signal transduction.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] A typical human B cell will have 50,000 to 100,000 antibodies bound to its surface.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Upon antigen binding, they cluster in large patches, which can exceed 1 micrometer in diameter, on lipid rafts that isolate the BCRs from most other cell signaling receptors.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These patches may improve the efficiency of the cellular immune response.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In humans, the cell surface is bare around the B cell receptors for several hundred nanometers, which further isolates the BCRs from competing influences.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies can come in different varieties known as *isotypes* or *classes*.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In humans there are five antibody classes known as IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, which are further subdivided into subclasses such as IgA1, IgA2.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The prefix "Ig" stands for *immunoglobulin*, while the suffix denotes the type of heavy chain the antibody contains: the heavy chain types α (alpha), γ (gamma), δ (delta), ε (epsilon), μ (mu) give rise to IgA, IgG, IgD, IgE, IgM, respectively.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The distinctive features of each class are determined by the part of the heavy chain within the hinge and Fc region.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The classes differ in their biological properties, functional locations and ability to deal with different antigens, as depicted in the table.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] For example, IgE antibodies are responsible for an allergic response consisting of histamine release from mast cells, often a sole contributor to asthma (though other pathways exist as do symptoms very similar to yet not technically asthma).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The variable region of these antibodies bind to allergic antigen, for example house dust mite particles, while its Fc region (in the ε heavy chains) binds to Fc receptor ε on a mast cell, triggering its degranulation: the release of molecules stored in its granules.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The antibody isotype of a B cell changes during cell development and activation.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Immature B cells, which have never been exposed to an antigen, express only the IgM isotype in a cell surface bound form.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The B lymphocyte, in this ready-to-respond form, is known as a "naive B lymphocyte." The naive B lymphocyte expresses both surface IgM and IgD.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The co-expression of both of these immunoglobulin isotypes renders the B cell ready to respond to antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] B cell activation follows engagement of the cell-bound antibody molecule with an antigen, causing the cell to divide and differentiate into an antibody-producing cell called a plasma cell.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This requires cytokines from T helper cells, unless antigen cross-links B cell receptors.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In this activated form, the B cell starts to produce antibody in a secreted form rather than a membrane-bound form.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Activated B cells that encounter certain signaling molecules undergo immunoglobulin class switching, also known as isotype switching, which causes the production of antibodies to change from IgM or IgD to the other antibody isotypes, IgE, IgA, or IgG.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In mammals there are two types of immunoglobulin light chain, which are called lambda (λ) and kappa (κ).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] However, there is no known functional difference between them, and both can occur with any of the five major types of heavy chains.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Each antibody contains two identical light chains: both κ or both λ.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Proportions of κ and λ types vary by species and can be used to detect abnormal proliferation of B cell clones.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Other types of light chains, such as the iota (ι) chain, are found in other vertebrates like sharks (Chondrichthyes) and bony fishes (Teleostei).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Though there is no known functional significance to the different choice of light chain class, the ratio of light chains can be diagnostically useful.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] For example, humans normally have a ratio of 2:1 of κ:λ light chains, and significant deviation from this ratio can indicate the presence of a monoclonal gammopathy (in which there is a proliferation of a plasma cell which may or may not be pre-malignant or malignant).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In most placental mammals, the structure of antibodies is generally similar.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Jawed fish appear to be the most primitive animals that are able to make antibodies similar to those of mammals, although many features of their adaptive immunity appeared somewhat earlier.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Cartilaginous fish (such as sharks) produce heavy-chain-only antibodies (i.e., lacking light chains) which moreover feature longer chain pentamers (with five constant units per molecule).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Camelids (such as camels, llamas, alpacas) are also notable for producing heavy-chain-only antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The antibody's paratope interacts with the antigen's epitope.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] An antigen usually contains different epitopes along its surface arranged discontinuously, and dominant epitopes on a given antigen are called determinants.Antibody and antigen interact by spatial complementarity (lock and key).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The molecular forces involved in the Fab-epitope interaction are weak and non-specific – for example electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, and van der Waals forces.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This means binding between antibody and antigen is reversible, and the antibody's affinity towards an antigen is relative rather than absolute.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Relatively weak binding also means it is possible for an antibody to cross-react with different antigens of different relative affinities.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] More indirectly, an antibody can signal immune cells to present antibody fragments to T cells, or downregulate other immune cells to avoid autoimmunity.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] At the prenatal and neonatal stages of life, the presence of antibodies is provided by passive immunity from the mother through transplacental transfer of IgG antibodies and breastmilk antibodies (predominantly secretory IgA in humans).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] There are also important species-specific differences in the structure of the placenta, which complicates interpretations of how placental transfer of antibody works in humans.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Early endogenous antibody production varies for different kinds of antibodies, and usually appear within the first years of life.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Since antibodies exist freely in the bloodstream, they are said to be part of the humoral immune system.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Circulating antibodies (other than natural IgM) are produced by clonal B cells that specifically respond to only one antigen (unless the antibodies recognize an epitope with structural similarity across many different antigens).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies will also trigger vasoactive amine degranulation to contribute to immunity against certain types of antigens (helminths, allergens).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies that bind to surface antigens (for example, on bacteria) will attract the first component of the complement cascade with their Fc region and initiate activation of the "classical" complement system.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This results in the killing of bacteria in two ways.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] First, the binding of the antibody and complement molecules marks the microbe for ingestion by phagocytes in a process called opsonization; these phagocytes are attracted by certain complement molecules generated in the complement cascade.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Second, some complement system components form a membrane attack complex to assist antibodies to kill the bacterium directly (bacteriolysis).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] To combat pathogens that replicate outside cells, antibodies bind to pathogens to link them together, causing them to agglutinate.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Since an antibody has at least two paratopes, it can bind more than one antigen by binding identical epitopes carried on the surfaces of these antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] By coating the pathogen, antibodies stimulate effector functions against the pathogen in cells that recognize their Fc region.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Those cells that recognize coated pathogens have Fc receptors, which, as the name suggests, interact with the Fc region of IgA, IgG, and IgE antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The activation of natural killer cells by antibodies initiates a cytotoxic mechanism known as antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity (ADCC) – this process may explain the efficacy of monoclonal antibodies used in biological therapies against cancer.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The Fc receptors are isotype-specific, which gives greater flexibility to the immune system, invoking only the appropriate immune mechanisms for distinct pathogens.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Humans and higher primates also produce "natural antibodies" that are present in serum before viral infection.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Natural antibodies have been defined as antibodies that are produced without any previous infection, vaccination, other foreign antigen exposure or passive immunization.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These antibodies can activate the classical complement pathway leading to lysis of enveloped virus particles long before the adaptive immune response is activated.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies are produced exclusively by B cells in response to antigens where initially, antibodies are formed as membrane-bound receptors, but upon activation by antigens and helper T cells, B cells differentiate to produce soluble antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Many natural antibodies are directed against the disaccharide galactose α(1,3)-galactose (α-Gal), which is found as a terminal sugar on glycosylated cell surface proteins, and generated in response to production of this sugar by bacteria contained in the human gut.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These antibodies undergo quality checks in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), which contains proteins that assist in proper folding and assembly.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Rejection of xenotransplantated organs is thought to be, in part, the result of natural antibodies circulating in the serum of the recipient binding to α-Gal antigens expressed on the donor tissue.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibodies are central to the immune protection elicited by most vaccines (although other components of the immune system certainly participate and for some diseases are considerably more important than antibodies in generating an immune response, such as in the case of shingles).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] At the same time, many microbes of medical importance have the ability to mutate to escape antibodies elicited by prior infections, and long-lived plasma cells cannot undergo affinity maturation or class switching.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This is compensated for through memory B cells: novel variants of a microbe that still retain structural features of previously encountered antigens can elicit memory B cell responses that adapt to those changes.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] It has been suggested that long-lived plasma cells secrete B cell receptors with higher affinity than those on the surfaces of memory B cells, but findings are not entirely consistent on this point.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Virtually all microbes can trigger an antibody response.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Successful recognition and eradication of many different types of microbes requires diversity among antibodies; their amino acid composition varies allowing them to interact with many different antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] It has been estimated that humans generate about 10 billion different antibodies, each capable of binding a distinct epitope of an antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Although a huge repertoire of different antibodies is generated in a single individual, the number of genes available to make these proteins is limited by the size of the human genome.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Several complex genetic mechanisms have evolved that allow vertebrate B cells to generate a diverse pool of antibodies from a relatively small number of antibody genes.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] One of these domains is called the variable domain, which is present in each heavy and light chain of every antibody, but can differ in different antibodies generated from distinct B cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Differences between the variable domains are located on three loops known as hypervariable regions (HV-1, HV-2 and HV-3) or complementarity-determining regions (CDR1, CDR2 and CDR3).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] CDRs are supported within the variable domains by conserved framework regions.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The heavy chain locus contains about 65 different variable domain genes that all differ in their CDRs.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Combining these genes with an array of genes for other domains of the antibody generates a large cavalry of antibodies with a high degree of variability.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This combination is called V(D)J recombination and discussed below.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Somatic recombination of immunoglobulins, also known as *V(D)J recombination*, involves the generation of a unique immunoglobulin variable region.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The variable region of each immunoglobulin heavy or light chain is encoded in several pieces—known as gene segments (subgenes).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These segments are called variable (V), diversity (D) and joining (J) segments.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] V, D and J segments are found in Ig heavy chains, but only V and J segments are found in Ig light chains.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Multiple copies of the V, D and J gene segments exist, and are tandemly arranged in the genomes of mammals.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In the bone marrow, each developing B cell will assemble an immunoglobulin variable region by randomly selecting and combining one V, one D and one J gene segment (or one V and one J segment in the light chain).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] As there are multiple copies of each type of gene segment, and different combinations of gene segments can be used to generate each immunoglobulin variable region, this process generates a huge number of antibodies, each with different paratopes, and thus different antigen specificities.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The rearrangement of several subgenes (i.e.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] V2 family) for lambda light chain immunoglobulin is coupled with the activation of microRNA miR-650, which further influences biology of B-cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] RAG proteins play an important role with V(D)J recombination in cutting DNA at a particular region.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Without the presence of these proteins, V(D)J recombination would not occur.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] After a B cell produces a functional immunoglobulin gene during V(D)J recombination, it cannot express any other variable region (a process known as allelic exclusion) thus each B cell can produce antibodies containing only one kind of variable chain.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Following activation with antigen, B cells begin to proliferate rapidly.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In these rapidly dividing cells, the genes encoding the variable domains of the heavy and light chains undergo a high rate of point mutation, by a process called *somatic hypermutation* (SHM).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] SHM results in approximately one nucleotide change per variable gene, per cell division.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] As a consequence, any daughter B cells will acquire slight amino acid differences in the variable domains of their antibody chains.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This serves to increase the diversity of the antibody pool and impacts the antibody's antigen-binding affinity.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Some point mutations will result in the production of antibodies that have a weaker interaction (low affinity) with their antigen than the original antibody, and some mutations will generate antibodies with a stronger interaction (high affinity).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] B cells that express high affinity antibodies on their surface will receive a strong survival signal during interactions with other cells, whereas those with low affinity antibodies will not, and will die by apoptosis.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Thus, B cells expressing antibodies with a higher affinity for the antigen will outcompete those with weaker affinities for function and survival allowing the average affinity of antibodies to increase over time.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The process of generating antibodies with increased binding affinities is called *affinity maturation*.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Affinity maturation occurs in mature B cells after V(D)J recombination, and is dependent on help from helper T cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Isotype or class switching is a biological process occurring after activation of the B cell, which allows the cell to produce different classes of antibody (IgA, IgE, or IgG).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The different classes of antibody, and thus effector functions, are defined by the constant (C) regions of the immunoglobulin heavy chain.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Initially, naive B cells express only cell-surface IgM and IgD with identical antigen binding regions.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Each isotype is adapted for a distinct function; therefore, after activation, an antibody with an IgG, IgA, or IgE effector function might be required to effectively eliminate an antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Class switching allows different daughter cells from the same activated B cell to produce antibodies of different isotypes.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Only the constant region of the antibody heavy chain changes during class switching; the variable regions, and therefore antigen specificity, remain unchanged.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Thus the progeny of a single B cell can produce antibodies, all specific for the same antigen, but with the ability to produce the effector function appropriate for each antigenic challenge.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Class switching is triggered by cytokines; the isotype generated depends on which cytokines are present in the B cell environment.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Class switching occurs in the heavy chain gene locus by a mechanism called class switch recombination (CSR).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This mechanism relies on conserved nucleotide motifs, called *switch (S) regions*, found in DNA upstream of each constant region gene (except in the δ-chain).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The DNA strand is broken by the activity of a series of enzymes at two selected S-regions.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The variable domain exon is rejoined through a process called non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) to the desired constant region (γ, α or ε).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This process results in an immunoglobulin gene that encodes an antibody of a different isotype.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] An antibody can be called *monospecific* if it has specificity for a single antigen or epitope, or bispecific if it has affinity for two different antigens or two different epitopes on the same antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] A group of antibodies can be called *polyvalent* (or *unspecific*) if they have affinity for various antigens or microorganisms.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Intravenous immunoglobulin, if not otherwise noted, consists of a variety of different IgG (polyclonal IgG).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In contrast, monoclonal antibodies are identical antibodies produced by a single B cell.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Heterodimeric antibodies, which are also asymmetrical antibodies, allow for greater flexibility and new formats for attaching a variety of drugs to the antibody arms.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] One of the general formats for a heterodimeric antibody is the "knobs-into-holes" format.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This format is specific to the heavy chain part of the constant region in antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The "knobs" part is engineered by replacing a small amino acid with a larger one.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] It fits into the "hole", which is engineered by replacing a large amino acid with a smaller one.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] What connects the "knobs" to the "holes" are the disulfide bonds between each chain.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The "knobs-into-holes" shape facilitates antibody dependent cell mediated cytotoxicity.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Single-chain variable fragments (scFv) are connected to the variable domain of the heavy and light chain via a short linker peptide.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The linker is rich in glycine, which gives it more flexibility, and serine/threonine, which gives it specificity.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Two different scFv fragments can be connected together, via a hinge region, to the constant domain of the heavy chain or the constant domain of the light chain.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This gives the antibody bispecificity, allowing for the binding specificities of two different antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The "knobs-into-holes" format enhances heterodimer formation but does not suppress homodimer formation.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] To further improve the function of heterodimeric antibodies, many scientists are looking towards artificial constructs.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Artificial antibodies are largely diverse protein motifs that use the functional strategy of the antibody molecule, but are not limited by the loop and framework structural constraints of the natural antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Controlling the combinational design of the sequence and the resulting three-dimensional space could enhance the natural design and allow for the attachment of different combinations of drugs to the arms.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Heterodimeric antibodies have a greater range in shapes they can take and the drugs that are attached to the arms do not have to be the same on each arm, allowing for different combinations of drugs to be used in cancer treatment.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Pharmaceuticals are able to produce highly functional bispecific, and even multispecific, antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The degree to which they can function is impressive given that such a change of shape from the natural form should lead to decreased functionality.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Antibody diversification typically occurs through somatic hypermutation, class switching, and affinity maturation targeting the BCR gene loci, but on occasion more unconventional forms of diversification have been documented.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] For example, in the case of malaria caused by *Plasmodium falciparum,* some antibodies from those who had been infected demonstrated an insertion from chromosome 19 containing a 98-amino acid stretch from leukocyte-associated immunoglobulin-like receptor 1, LAIR1, in the elbow joint.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This represents a form of interchromosomal transposition.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] LAIR1 normally binds collagen, but can recognize repetitive interspersed families of polypeptides (RIFIN) family members that are highly expressed on the surface of *P. falciparum*-infected red blood cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In fact, these antibodies underwent affinity maturation that enhanced affinity for RIFIN but abolished affinity for collagen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] These "LAIR1-containing" antibodies have been found in 5-10% of donors from Tanzania and Mali, though not in European donors.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] European donors did show 100-1000 nucleotide stretches inside the elbow joints as well, however.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] This particular phenomenon may be specific to malaria, as infection is known to induce genomic instability.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The first use of the term "antibody" occurred in a text by Paul Ehrlich.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The term *Antikörper* (the German word for *antibody*) appears in the conclusion of his article "Experimental Studies on Immunity", published in October 1891, which states that, "if two substances give rise to two different *Antikörper*, then they themselves must be different".
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] However, the term was not accepted immediately and several other terms for antibody were proposed; these included *Immunkörper*, *Amboceptor*, *Zwischenkörper*, *substance sensibilisatrice*, *copula*, *Desmon*, *philocytase*, *fixateur*, and *Immunisin*.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The word *antibody* has formal analogy to the word *antitoxin* and a similar concept to *Immunkörper* (*immune body* in English).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] As such, the original construction of the word contains a logical flaw; the antitoxin is something directed against a toxin, while the antibody is a body directed against something.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The study of antibodies began in 1890 when Emil von Behring and Kitasato Shibasaburō described antibody activity against diphtheria and tetanus toxins.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Von Behring and Kitasato put forward the theory of humoral immunity, proposing that a mediator in serum could react with a foreign antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Other researchers believed that antibodies existed freely in the blood and, in 1904, Almroth Wright suggested that soluble antibodies coated bacteria to label them for phagocytosis and killing; a process that he named opsoninization.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In the 1920s, Michael Heidelberger and Oswald Avery observed that antigens could be precipitated by antibodies and went on to show that antibodies are made of protein.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The biochemical properties of antigen-antibody-binding interactions were examined in more detail in the late 1930s by John Marrack.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The next major advance was in the 1940s, when Linus Pauling confirmed the lock-and-key theory proposed by Ehrlich by showing that the interactions between antibodies and antigens depend more on their shape than their chemical composition.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In 1948, Astrid Fagraeus discovered that B cells, in the form of plasma cells, were responsible for generating antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Further work concentrated on characterizing the structures of the antibody proteins.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] A major advance in these structural studies was the discovery in the early 1960s by Gerald Edelman and Joseph Gally of the antibody light chain, and their realization that this protein is the same as the Bence-Jones protein described in 1845 by Henry Bence Jones.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Edelman went on to discover that antibodies are composed of disulfide bond-linked heavy and light chains.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Around the same time, antibody-binding (Fab) and antibody tail (Fc) regions of IgG were characterized by Rodney Porter.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Together, these scientists deduced the structure and complete amino acid sequence of IgG, a feat for which they were jointly awarded the 1972 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] The Fv fragment was prepared and characterized by David Givol.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] While most of these early studies focused on IgM and IgG, other immunoglobulin isotypes were identified in the 1960s: Thomas Tomasi discovered secretory antibody (IgA); David S.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] Fahey discovered IgD; and Kimishige Ishizaka and Teruko Ishizaka discovered IgE and showed it was a class of antibodies involved in allergic reactions.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p01] In a landmark series of experiments beginning in 1976, Susumu Tonegawa showed that genetic material can rearrange itself to form the vast array of available antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Detection of particular antibodies is a very common form of medical diagnostics, and applications such as serology depend on these methods.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] For example, in biochemical assays for disease diagnosis, a titer of antibodies directed against Epstein–Barr virus or Lyme disease is estimated from the blood.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] If those antibodies are not present, either the person is not infected or the infection occurred a *very* long time ago, and the B cells generating these specific antibodies have naturally decayed.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] In clinical immunology, levels of individual classes of immunoglobulins are measured by nephelometry (or turbidimetry) to characterize the antibody profile of patient.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Elevations in different classes of immunoglobulins are sometimes useful in determining the cause of liver damage in patients for whom the diagnosis is unclear.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] For example, IgM levels are often elevated in patients with primary biliary cirrhosis, whereas IgA deposition along hepatic sinusoids can suggest alcoholic liver disease.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Autoimmune disorders can often be traced to antibodies that bind the body's own epitopes; many can be detected through blood tests.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibodies directed against red blood cell surface antigens in immune mediated hemolytic anemia are detected with the Coombs test.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] The Coombs test is also used for antibody screening in blood transfusion preparation and also for antibody screening in antenatal women.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] New dioxaborolane chemistry enables radioactive fluoride (18F) labeling of antibodies, which allows for positron emission tomography (PET) imaging of cancer.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Targeted monoclonal antibody therapy is employed to treat diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, multiple sclerosis, psoriasis, and many forms of cancer including non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, colorectal cancer, head and neck cancer and breast cancer.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Some immune deficiencies, such as X-linked agammaglobulinemia and hypogammaglobulinemia, result in partial or complete lack of antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] These diseases are often treated by inducing a short-term form of immunity called passive immunity.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Passive immunity is achieved through the transfer of ready-made antibodies in the form of human or animal serum, pooled immunoglobulin or monoclonal antibodies, into the affected individual.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Rh factor, also known as Rh D antigen, is an antigen found on red blood cells; individuals that are Rh-positive (Rh+) have this antigen on their red blood cells and individuals that are Rh-negative (Rh–) do not.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] During normal childbirth, delivery trauma or complications during pregnancy, blood from a fetus can enter the mother's system.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] In the case of an Rh-incompatible mother and child, consequential blood mixing may sensitize an Rh- mother to the Rh antigen on the blood cells of the Rh+ child, putting the remainder of the pregnancy, and any subsequent pregnancies, at risk for hemolytic disease of the newborn.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Rho(D) immune globulin antibodies are specific for human RhD antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Anti-RhD antibodies are administered as part of a prenatal treatment regimen to prevent sensitization that may occur when a Rh-negative mother has a Rh-positive fetus.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Treatment of a mother with Anti-RhD antibodies prior to and immediately after trauma and delivery destroys Rh antigen in the mother's system from the fetus.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] This occurs before the antigen can stimulate maternal B cells to "remember" Rh antigen by generating memory B cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Therefore, her humoral immune system will not make anti-Rh antibodies, and will not attack the Rh antigens of the current or subsequent babies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Rho(D) Immune Globulin treatment prevents sensitization that can lead to Rh disease, but does not prevent or treat the underlying disease itself.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Specific antibodies are produced by injecting an antigen into a mammal, such as a mouse, rat, rabbit, goat, sheep, horse, or human for large quantities of antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Blood isolated from these animals contains *polyclonal antibodies*—multiple antibodies that bind to the same antigen—in the serum, which can now be called antiserum.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] (For medical products, the horse and the human are most commonly used: the former for its large blood volume and high antibody titers, the latter for a higher compatibility with other humans.) Antigens are also injected into chickens for generation of polyclonal antibodies in egg yolk.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] To obtain antibody that is specific for a single epitope of an antigen, antibody-secreting lymphocytes are isolated from the animal and immortalized by fusing them with a cancer cell line.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] The fused cells are called hybridomas, and will continually grow and secrete antibody in culture.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Single hybridoma cells are isolated by dilution cloning to generate cell clones that all produce the same antibody; these antibodies are called *monoclonal antibodies*.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies are often purified using Protein A/G or antigen-affinity chromatography.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] In research, purified antibodies are used in many applications.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibodies for research applications can be found directly from antibody suppliers, or through use of a specialist search engine.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Research antibodies are most commonly used to identify and locate intracellular and extracellular proteins.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibodies are used in flow cytometry to differentiate cell types by the proteins they express; different types of cells express different combinations of cluster of differentiation molecules on their surface, and produce different intracellular and secretable proteins.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Proteins can also be detected and quantified with antibodies, using ELISA and ELISpot techniques.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Multiple attempts have been made to improve both the way that researchers validate antibodies and ways in which they report on antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Researchers using antibodies in their work need to record them correctly in order to allow their research to be reproducible (and therefore tested, and qualified by other researchers).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Less than half of research antibodies referenced in academic papers can be easily identified.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Papers published in F1000 in 2014 and 2015 provide researchers with a guide for reporting research antibody use.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] The RRID paper, is co-published in 4 journals that implemented the RRIDs Standard for research resource citation, which draws data from the antibodyregistry.org as the source of antibody identifiers (see also group at Force11).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibody regions can be used to further biomedical research by acting as a guide for drugs to reach their target.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibodies and Fc‑based constructs provide highly specific binding to cell-surface receptors and are used as targeting moieties in antibody–drug conjugates (ADCs), bispecifics, and Fc‑fusion drugs for cancer and other diseases.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] There are several ways to obtain antibodies, including *in vivo* techniques like animal immunization and various *in vitro* approaches, such as the phage display method.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Traditionally, most antibodies are produced by hybridoma cell lines through immortalization of antibody-producing cells by chemically induced fusion with myeloma cells.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] In some cases, additional fusions with other lines have created "triomas" and "quadromas".
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] The manufacturing process should be appropriately described and validated.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] The importance of antibodies in health care and the biotechnology industry demands knowledge of their structures at high resolution.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] This information is used for protein engineering, modifying the antigen binding affinity, and identifying an epitope, of a given antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] X-ray crystallography is one commonly used method for determining antibody structures.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] However, crystallizing an antibody is often laborious and time-consuming.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Computational approaches provide a cheaper and faster alternative to crystallography, but their results are more equivocal, since they do not produce empirical structures.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Online web servers such as *Web Antibody Modeling* (WAM) and *Prediction of Immunoglobulin Structure* (PIGS) enable computational modeling of antibody variable regions.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] The ability to describe the antibody through binding affinity to the antigen is supplemented by information on antibody structure and amino acid sequences for the purpose of patent claims.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Several methods have been presented for computational design of antibodies based on the structural bioinformatics studies of antibody CDRs.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] There are a variety of methods used to sequence an antibody including Edman degradation, cDNA, etc.; albeit one of the most common modern uses for peptide/protein identification is liquid chromatography coupled with tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS).
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] High volume antibody sequencing methods require computational approaches for the data analysis, including de novo sequencing directly from tandem mass spectra and database search methods that use existing protein sequence databases.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Many versions of shotgun protein sequencing are able to increase the coverage by utilizing CID/HCD/ETD fragmentation methods and other techniques, and they have achieved substantial progress in attempt to fully sequence proteins, especially antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Other methods have assumed the existence of similar proteins, a known genome sequence, or combined top-down and bottom up approaches.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Current technologies have the ability to assemble protein sequences with high accuracy by integrating de novo sequencing peptides, intensity, and positional confidence scores from database and homology searches.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibody mimetics are organic compounds, like antibodies, that can specifically bind antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] They consist of artificial peptides or proteins, or aptamer-based nucleic acid molecules with a molar mass of about 3 to 20 kDa.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibody fragments, such as Fab and nanobodies are not considered as antibody mimetics.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Common advantages over antibodies are better solubility, tissue penetration, stability towards heat and enzymes, and comparatively low production costs.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] Antibody mimetics have been developed and commercialized as research, diagnostic and therapeutic agents.
[src:antibody-structure/antibody-p02] BAU (binding antibody unit, often as BAU/mL) is a measurement unit defined by the WHO for the comparison of assays detecting the same class of immunoglobulins with the same specificity.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Antibody–antigen interactions are highly specific and those that have high affinity will interact with increased bond strength and trigger downstream immune responses.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The strength of the bond between the epitope of the antigen and the paratope of the antibody will determine the affinity of the interaction.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] There are three CDRs (CDR1, CDR2 and CDR3), arranged non-consecutively, on the amino acid sequence of a variable domain of an antigen receptor.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Three can be found on the Light-chain, named L1 through L3, and three on the Heavy-chain, named H1 through H3.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Since the antigen receptors are typically composed of two variable domains (on two different polypeptide chains, heavy and light chain), there are six CDRs for each antigen receptor that can collectively come into contact with the antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] A typical monoclonal antibody molecule has two antigen receptors and therefore contains twelve CDRs total.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] There are three CDR loops per variable domain in antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Sixty CDRs can be found on a pentameric IgM molecule, which is composed of five antibodies and has increased avidity as a result of the collective affinity of all antigen-binding sites combined.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Since most sequence variation associated with immunoglobulins and T cell receptors are found in the CDRs, these regions are sometimes referred to as *hypervariable regions*.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Within the variable *domain*, CDR1 and CDR2 are found in the variable (V) *region* of a polypeptide chain, and CDR3 includes some of V, all of diversity (D, heavy chains only) and joining (J) regions.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The V region sequence undergoes rearrangement during B-cell development, called somatic recombination.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] This rearrangement of the V-region is where the CDR-L3 and CDR-H3 are encoded and diversified, whereas the other four CDRs are generated in the germ-line.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The diversification of the CDR-H3 will ultimately give antibodies their specificity, and ability to recognize antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Other factors contribute to the antibody-antigen interaction, including amino acid residues.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Residues located in particular positions of a CDR loop are used to classify canonical structures.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Uncharged-polar residues, especially Serine and Tyrosine, are found in CDRs at a high concentration ratio.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] These residues significantly contribute to the direct hydrogen bonds between the antigen and the antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Hydrogen bond interactions will induce the enzymatic activity of an enzyme; therefore, the more hydrogen bonds that are present at the antibody-antigen binding site will result in a stronger, more stable binding structure.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The tertiary structure of an antibody is important to analyze and design new antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The structure and sequence of all six CDRs combined will determine the binding activity of the antigen receptor on an antibody or T-cell receptor.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] CDRs have been separated into canonical classes based on their varying loop lengths, which are commonly used to differentiate the CDRs from each other.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The structural relationship between different length CDRS is based on length-independent components, such as their sequence, and can further characterize CDRs.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The loops, or three-dimensional structures of the non-H3 CDRs (all CDRs but H3) of antibodies have been clustered and classified by Chothia et al. and more recently by North et al.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] Homology modeling is a computational method to build tertiary structures from amino-acid sequences.
[src:antibody-structure/complementarity-determining-region] The so-called H3-rules are empirical rules to build models of CDR3.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] An **epitope**, also known as **antigenic determinant**, is the part of an antigen that is recognized by the immune system, specifically by antibodies, B cells, or T cells.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] The part of an antibody that binds to the epitope is called a paratope.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Although epitopes are usually non-self proteins, sequences derived from the host that can be recognized (as in the case of autoimmune diseases) are also epitopes.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] The epitopes of protein antigens are divided into two categories, conformational epitopes and linear epitopes, based on their structure and interaction with the paratope.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Conformational and linear epitopes interact with the paratope based on the 3-D conformation adopted by the epitope, which is determined by the surface features of the involved epitope residues and the shape or tertiary structure of other segments of the antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] A conformational epitope is formed by the 3-D conformation adopted by the interaction of discontiguous amino acid residues.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] In contrast, a linear epitope is formed by the 3-D conformation adopted by the interaction of contiguous amino acid residues.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] A linear epitope is not determined solely by the primary structure of the involved amino acids.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Residues that flank such amino acid residues, as well as more distant amino acid residues of the antigen affect the ability of the primary structure residues to adopt the epitope's 3-D conformation.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] T cell epitopes are presented on the surface of an antigen-presenting cell, where they are bound to major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] In humans, professional antigen-presenting cells are specialized to present MHC class II peptides, whereas most nucleated somatic cells present MHC class I peptides.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] T cell epitopes presented by MHC class I molecules are typically peptides between 8 and 11 amino acids in length, whereas MHC class II molecules present longer peptides, 13–17 amino acids in length, and non-classical MHC molecules also present non-peptidic epitopes such as glycolipids.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] The part of the antigen that immunoglobulin or antibodies bind to is called a B-cell epitope.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] B cell epitopes can be divided into two groups: conformational or linear.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] B cell epitopes are mainly conformational.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] There are additional epitope types when the quaternary structure is considered.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Epitopes that are masked when protein subunits aggregate are called cryptotopes.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Neotopes are epitopes that are only recognized while in a specific quaternary structure and the residues of the epitope can span multiple protein subunits.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Neotopes are not recognized once the subunits dissociate.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] This property is exploited by the immune system in regulation by anti-idiotypic antibodies (originally proposed by Nobel laureate Niels Kaj Jerne).
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] If an antibody binds to an antigen's epitope, the paratope could become the epitope for another antibody that will then bind to it.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] If this second antibody is of IgM class, its binding can upregulate the immune response; if the second antibody is of IgG class, its binding can downregulate the immune response.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] MHC class I and II epitopes can be reliably predicted by computational means alone, although not all in-silico T cell epitope prediction algorithms are equivalent in their accuracy.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] There are two main methods of predicting peptide-MHC binding: data-driven and structure-based.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Structure based methods model the peptide-MHC structure and require great computational power.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Data-driven methods have higher predictive performance than structure-based methods.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Data-driven methods predict peptide-MHC binding based on peptide sequences that bind MHC molecules.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] By identifying T-cell epitopes, scientists can track, phenotype, and stimulate T-cells.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] There are two main methods of epitope mapping: either structural or functional studies.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Methods for structurally mapping epitopes include X-ray crystallography, nuclear magnetic resonance, and electron microscopy.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] X-ray crystallography of Ag-Ab complexes is considered an accurate way to structurally map epitopes.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Nuclear magnetic resonance can be used to map epitopes by using data about the Ag-Ab complex.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] This method does not require crystal formation but can only work on small peptides and proteins.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Electron microscopy is a low-resolution method that can localize epitopes on larger antigens like virus particles.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Methods for functionally mapping epitopes often use binding assays such as western blot, dot blot, and/or ELISA to determine antibody binding.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Competition methods look to determine if two monoclonal antibodies (mABs) can bind to an antigen at the same time or compete with each other to bind at the same site.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Another technique involves high-throughput mutagenesis, an epitope mapping strategy developed to improve rapid mapping of conformational epitopes on structurally complex proteins.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Mutagenesis uses randomly/site-directed mutations at individual residues to map epitopes.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] B-cell epitope mapping can be used for the development of antibody therapeutics, peptide-based vaccines, and immunodiagnostic tools.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Epitopes are often used in proteomics and the study of other gene products.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Using recombinant DNA techniques genetic sequences coding for epitopes that are recognized by common antibodies can be fused to the gene.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Following synthesis, the resulting epitope tag allows the antibody to find the protein or other gene product enabling lab techniques for localisation, purification, and further molecular characterization including identifying the protein's binding partners.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Common epitopes used for this purpose are Myc-tag, HA-tag, FLAG-tag, GST-tag, 6xHis, V5-tag and OLLAS.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] An epitope tag was first described by Munro and Pelham to detect and track proteins in 1984 .
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Tags were quickly adapted for purifying proteins and to detect, pull down, and clone interaction partners of proteins .
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] These tags were originally referred to as "peptide tag", "epitope insertion", "marker sequence", and "epitope addition" , until "epitope tag" was coined and popularized.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Peptides can also be bound by proteins that form covalent bonds to the peptide, allowing irreversible immobilisation.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] These strategies have also been successfully applied to the development of "epitope-focused" vaccine design.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] The first epitope-based vaccine was developed in 1985 by Chaim Jacob and colleagues from The Weizmann Institute of Science.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Epitope-based vaccines stimulate humoral and cellular immune responses using isolated B-cell or T-cell epitopes.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] These vaccines can use multiple epitopes to increase their efficacy.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] To find epitopes to use for the vaccine, in silico mapping is often used.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Once candidate epitopes are found, the constructs are engineered and tested for vaccine efficiency.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] While epitope-based vaccines are generally safe, one possible side effect is cytokine storms.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] A **neoantigenic determinant** is an epitope on a neoantigen, which is a newly formed antigen that has not been previously recognized by the immune system.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Neoantigens are often associated with tumor antigens and are found in oncogenic cells.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Neoantigens and, by extension, neoantigenic determinants can be formed when a protein undergoes further modification within a biochemical pathway such as glycosylation, phosphorylation or proteolysis.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] This, by altering the structure of the protein, can produce new epitopes that are called neoantigenic determinants as they give rise to new antigenic determinants.
[src:antibody-structure/epitope] Recognition requires separate, specific antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The **fragment antigen-binding region** (**Fab region**) is a region on an antibody that binds to antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] It is composed of one constant and one variable domain of each of the heavy and the light chain.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The variable domain contains the paratope (the antigen-binding site), comprising a set of complementarity-determining regions, at the amino terminal end of the monomer.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Each arm of the Y thus binds an epitope on the antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] In an experimental setting, Fc and Fab fragments can be generated in the laboratory.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The enzyme papain can be used to cleave an immunoglobulin monomer into two Fab fragments and an Fc fragment.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Conversely, the enzyme pepsin cleaves below the hinge region, so the result instead is a **F(ab')2 fragment** and a pFc' fragment.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Recently another enzyme for generation of F(ab')2 has been commercially available.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The enzyme IdeS (Immunoglobulin degrading enzyme from *Streptococcus pyogenes*, trade name FabRICATOR) cleaves IgG in a sequence specific manner at neutral pH.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The F(ab')2 fragment can be split into two **Fab'** fragments by mild reduction.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The variable regions of the heavy and light chains can be fused together to form a single-chain variable fragment (scFv), which is only half the size of the Fab fragment, yet retains the original specificity of the parent immunoglobulin.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Fabs have seen some therapeutic use in emergency medicine as an antidote.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Marketed applications include digoxin immune fab and Crofab, a mixture of Fabs for rattlesnake bites.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Fabs against colchicine and tricyclic antidepressants has also been produced but are yet to see approval.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Compared to whole non-human antibodies, Fab' and F(ab')2 antibodies are less likely to trigger anaphylaxis, as the species-related Fc region is removed.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Fabs are a common form-factor for monoclonal antibodies designated for therapeutic use.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] The Fab abciximab, which inhibits blood clotting, works by disabling glycoprotein IIb/IIIa found on platelets.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Ranibizumab, a treatment for macular degeneration, targets vascular endothelial growth factor A, a protein involved in the growth of blood vessels.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Certolizumab pegol is a Fab chemically linked to PEG, and it treats various inflammatory disorders by binding away TNFα.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Fab antibodies also have diagnostic use.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Arcitumomab is a mouse antibody that recognizes carcinoembryonic antigen, an antigen over-expressed in 95% of colorectal cancers.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] It is conjugated to a radioactive element, which will label the tumors when viewed with single-photon emission computed tomography.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Sulesomab, an antigen that recognizes proteins on the surface of granulocytes, is used to label out infections, again using the 99mTc isotope.
[src:antibody-structure/fragment-antigen-binding] Fab fragments are often fused to small proteins (<100 kDa) that have lower scattering, resulting in images with less contrast.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Antibodies are major components of humoral immunity.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] IgG is the main type of antibody found in blood and extracellular fluid, allowing it to control infection of body tissues.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] By binding many kinds of pathogens such as viruses, bacteria, and fungi, IgG protects the body from infection.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] IgG antibodies are generated following class switching and maturation of the antibody response, thus they participate predominantly in the secondary immune response.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] IgG is secreted as a monomer, which is small in size, allowing it to easily diffuse into tissues.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] It is the only antibody isotype that has receptors to facilitate passage through the human placenta, thereby providing protection to the fetus *in utero*.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Along with IgA secreted in the breast milk, residual IgG absorbed through the placenta provides the neonate with humoral immunity before its own immune system develops.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Colostrum contains a high percentage of IgG, especially bovine colostrum.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] In individuals with prior immunity to a pathogen, IgG appears about 24–48 hours after antigenic stimulation.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Therefore, in the first six months of life, the newborn has the same antibodies as the mother and can defend itself against all the pathogens the mother encountered in her life (even if only through vaccination) until these antibodies are degraded.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] This repertoire of immunoglobulins is crucial for newborns, who are very sensitive to infections, especially in the respiratory and digestive systems.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] IgG is also involved in regulating allergic reactions.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] According to Finkelman, there are two pathways of systemic anaphylaxis: antigens can cause systemic anaphylaxis in mice through classic pathway by cross-linking IgE bound to the mast cell receptor FcεRI, stimulating the release of both histamine and platelet activating factor (PAF).
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] In the alternative pathway, antigens form complexes with IgG, which then cross-link the macrophage receptor FcγRIII, stimulating only PAF release.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] IgG antibodies can prevent IgE-mediated anaphylaxis by intercepting a specific antigen before it binds to mast cell–associated IgE.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Consequently, IgG antibodies block systemic anaphylaxis induced by small amounts of antigen, but can mediate systemic anaphylaxis induced by larger amounts.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] IgG antibodies are large globular proteins made of four peptide chains; two identical γ (gamma) heavy chains of about 50 kDa and two identical light chains of about 25 kDa.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The resulting tetrameric quaternary structure, therefore, has a total molecular weight of about 150 kDa.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The two heavy chains are linked to each other and to a light chain each by disulfide bonds.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The resulting tetramer has two identical halves, which together form a Y-like shape.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Each end of the fork contains an identical antigen binding site.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The Fc regions of IgGs bear a highly conserved N-glycosylation site at asparagine 297 in the constant region of the heavy chain.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The N-glycans attached to this site are predominantly core-fucosylated biantennary structures of the complex type.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] In addition, small amounts of these N-glycans also bear bisecting GlcNAc and α-2,6-linked sialic acid residues.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The N-glycan composition in IgG has been linked to several autoimmune, infectious and metabolic diseases.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] There are four IgG subclasses (IgG1, 2, 3, and 4) in humans, named in order of their abundance in serum (IgG1 being the most abundant).
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Note: IgG affinity to Fc receptors on phagocytic cells is specific to individual species from which the antibody comes as well as the class.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The structure of the hinge regions (region 6 in the diagram) contributes to the unique biological properties of each of the four IgG classes.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Even though there is about 95% similarity between their Fc regions, the structure of the hinge regions is relatively different.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] In 2013, the Temporal Model of human IgE and IgG function was proposed.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] This model suggests that IgG3 (and IgE) appear early in a response.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The IgG3, though of relatively low affinity, allows IgG-mediated defences to join IgM-mediated defences in clearing foreign antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Subsequently, higher affinity IgG1 and IgG2 are produced.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The relative balance of these subclasses, in any immune complexes that form, helps determine the strength of the inflammatory processes that follow.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Finally, if antigen persists, high affinity IgG4 is produced, which dampens down inflammation by helping to curtail FcR-mediated processes.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The relative ability of different IgG subclasses to fix complement may explain why some anti-donor antibody responses do harm a graft after organ transplantation.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] In a mouse model of autoantibody mediated anemia using IgG isotype switch variants of an anti erythrocytes autoantibody, it was found that mouse IgG2a was superior to IgG1 in activating complement.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Moreover, it was found that the IgG2a isotype was able to interact very efficiently with FcgammaR.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] As a result, 20 times higher doses of IgG1, in relationship to IgG2a autoantibodies, were required to induce autoantibody mediated pathology.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Since mouse IgG1 and human IgG1 are not entirely similar in function, and the inference of human antibody function from mouse studies must be done with great care.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] However, both human and mouse antibodies have different abilities to fix complement and to bind to Fc receptors.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] The measurement of immunoglobulin G can be a diagnostic tool for certain conditions, such as autoimmune hepatitis, if indicated by certain symptoms.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Clinically, measured IgG antibody levels are generally considered to be indicative of an individual's immune status to particular pathogens.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] A common example of this practice is titers drawn to demonstrate serologic immunity to measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR), hepatitis B virus, and varicella (chickenpox), among others.
[src:antibody-structure/immunoglobulin-g] Testing of IgG is not indicated for diagnosis of allergy, and there is no evidence that it has any relationship to food intolerances.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] In immunology, antibodies (immunoglobulins (Ig)) are classified into several types called **isotypes** or **classes**.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The variable (V) regions near the tip of the antibody can differ from molecule to molecule in countless ways, allowing it to specifically target an antigen (or more exactly, an epitope).
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] In contrast, the constant (C) regions only occur in a few variants, which define the antibody's class.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Antibodies of different classes activate distinct effector mechanisms in response to an antigen (triggering different elements of the innate immune system).
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] They appear at different stages of an immune response, differ in structural features, and in their location around the body.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Isotype expression reflects the maturation stage of a B cell.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Naive B cells express IgM and IgD isotypes with unmutated variable genes, which are produced from the same initial transcript following alternative splicing.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Expression of other antibody isotypes (in humans: IgG, IgA, and IgE) occurs via a process of class switching after antigen exposure.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Class switching is mediated by the enzyme AID (activation-induced cytidine deaminase) and occurs after the B cell binds an antigen through its B cell receptor.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Class-switching usually requires interaction with a T helper cell.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] There are also two light chain isotypes κ and λ; however, there is no significant difference in function between the two.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Thus an antibody isotype is determined by the constant regions of the heavy chains only.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgM is first expressed as a monomer on the surface of immature B cells.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Upon antigenic stimulation, IgM+ B cells secrete pentameric IgM antibody formed by five Ig monomers which are linked via disulfide bonds.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The pentamer also contains a polypeptide J-chain, which links two of the monomers and facilitates secretion at mucosal surfaces.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The pentameric structure of IgM antibodies makes them efficient at binding antigens with repetitive epitopes (e.g. bacterial capsule, viral capsid) and activation of complement cascade.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] As IgM antibodies are expressed early in a B cell response, they are rarely highly mutated and have broad antigen reactivity thus providing an early response to a wide range of antigens without the need for T cell help.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgD isotypes are expressed on naive B cells as they leave bone marrow and populate secondary lymphoid organs.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The levels of surface expression of IgD isotype has been associated with differences in B cell activation status but their role in serum is poorly understood.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The IgG, IgE and IgA antibody isotypes are generated following class-switching during germinal centre reaction and provide different effector functions in response to specific antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgG is the most abundant antibody class in the serum and it is divided into 4 subclasses based on differences in the structure of the constant region genes and the ability to trigger different effector functions.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Despite the high sequence similarity (90% identical on the amino acid level), each subclass has a different half-life, a unique profile of antigen binding and distinct capacity for complement activation.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgG1 antibodies are the most abundant IgG class and dominate the responses to protein antigens.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Impaired production of IgG1 is observed in some cases of immunodeficiency and is associated with recurrent infections.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The IgG responses to bacterial capsular polysaccharide antigens are mediated primarily via IgG2 subclass, and deficiencies in this subclass result in susceptibility to certain bacterial species.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgG2 represents the major antibody subclass reacting to glycan antigens but IgG1 and IgG3 subclasses have also been observed in such responses, particularly in the case of protein-glycan conjugates.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgG3 is an efficient activator of pro-inflammatory responses by triggering the classical complement pathway.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] It has the shortest half-life compared to the other IgG subclasses and is frequently present together with IgG1 in response to protein antigens after viral infections.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgG4 is the least abundant IgG subclass in the serum and is often generated following repeated exposure to the same antigen or during persistent infections.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgA antibodies are secreted in the respiratory or the intestinal tract and act as the main mediators of mucosal immunity.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] They are monomeric in the serum, but appear as a dimer termed secretory IgA (sIgA) at mucosal surfaces.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] The secretory IgA is associated with a J-chain and another polypeptide chain called the secretory component.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgA antibodies are divided into two subclasses that differ in the size of their hinge region.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgA1 has a longer hinge region which increases its sensitivity to bacterial proteases.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Therefore, this subclass dominates the serum IgA, while IgA2 is predominantly found in mucosal secretions.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] IgE antibodies are present at lowest concentrations in peripheral blood but constitute the main antibody class in allergic responses through the engagement of mast cells, eosinophils and Langerhans cells.
[src:antibody-structure/isotype-immunology] Responses to specific helminths are also characterised with elevated levels of IgE antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] A **monoclonal antibody** (**mAb**, more rarely called **moAb**) is an antibody produced from a cell lineage made by cloning a unique white blood cell.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] All subsequent antibodies derived this way trace back to a unique parent cell.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies are identical and can thus have monovalent affinity, binding only to a particular epitope (the part of an antigen that is recognized by the antibody).
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In contrast, polyclonal antibodies are mixtures of antibodies derived from multiple plasma cell lineages which each bind to their particular target epitope.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Artificial antibodies known as bispecific monoclonal antibodies can also be engineered which include two different antigen binding sites (FABs) on the same antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] It is possible to produce monoclonal antibodies that specifically bind to almost any suitable substance; they can then serve to detect or purify it.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This capability has become an investigative tool in biochemistry, molecular biology, and medicine.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies are used in the diagnosis of illnesses such as cancer and infections and are used therapeutically in the treatment of e.g. cancer and inflammatory diseases.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In the early 1900s, immunologist Paul Ehrlich proposed the idea of a *Zauberkugel* – "magic bullet", conceived of as a compound which selectively targeted a disease-causing organism, and could deliver a toxin for that organism.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This underpinned the concept of monoclonal antibodies and monoclonal drug conjugates.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Ehrlich and Élie Metchnikoff received the 1908 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine for providing the theoretical basis for immunology.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] By the 1970s, lymphocytes producing a single antibody were known, in the form of multiple myeloma – a cancer affecting B-cells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These abnormal antibodies or paraproteins were used to study the structure of antibodies, but it was not yet possible to produce identical antibodies specific to a given antigen.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In 1973, Jerrold Schwaber described the production of monoclonal antibodies using human–mouse hybrid cells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This work remains widely cited among those using human-derived hybridomas.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In 1975, Georges Köhler and César Milstein succeeded in making fusions of myeloma cell lines with B cells to create hybridomas that could produce antibodies, specific to known antigens and that were immortalized.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] They and Niels Kaj Jerne shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984 for the discovery.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In 1988, Gregory Winter and his team pioneered the techniques to humanize monoclonal antibodies, eliminating the reactions that many monoclonal antibodies caused in some patients.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] By the 1990s research was making progress in using monoclonal antibodies therapeutically, and in 2018, James P.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Allison and Tasuku Honjo received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discovery of cancer therapy by inhibition of negative immune regulation, using monoclonal antibodies that prevent inhibitory linkages.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The translational work needed to implement these ideas is credited to Lee Nadler.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] As explained in an NIH article, "He was the first to discover monoclonal antibodies directed against human B-cell–specific antigens and, in fact, all the known human B-cell–specific antigens were discovered in his laboratory.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Much of the work behind production of monoclonal antibodies is rooted in the production of hybridomas, which involves identifying antigen-specific plasma/plasmablast cells that produce antibodies specific to an antigen of interest and fusing these cells with myeloma cells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Rabbit B-cells can be used to form a rabbit hybridoma.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Polyethylene glycol is used to fuse adjacent plasma membranes, but the success rate is low, so a selective medium in which only fused cells can grow is used.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This is possible because myeloma cells have lost the ability to synthesize hypoxanthine-guanine-phosphoribosyl transferase (HGPRT), an enzyme necessary for the salvage synthesis of nucleic acids.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The absence of HGPRT is not a problem for these cells unless the de novo purine synthesis pathway is also disrupted.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Exposing cells to aminopterin (a folic acid analogue which inhibits dihydrofolate reductase) makes them unable to use the de novo pathway and become fully auxotrophic for nucleic acids, thus requiring supplementation to survive.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The selective culture medium is called HAT medium because it contains hypoxanthine, aminopterin and thymidine.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This medium is selective for fused (hybridoma) cells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Unfused myeloma cells cannot grow because they lack HGPRT and thus cannot replicate their DNA.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Unfused spleen cells cannot grow indefinitely because of their limited life span.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Only fused hybrid cells referred to as hybridomas, are able to grow indefinitely in the medium because the spleen cell partner supplies HGPRT and the myeloma partner has traits that make it immortal (similar to a cancer cell).
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This mixture of cells is then diluted and clones are grown from single parent cells on microtitre wells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The antibodies secreted by the different clones are then assayed for their ability to bind to the antigen (with a test such as ELISA or antigen microarray assay) or immuno-dot blot.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The most productive and stable clone is then selected for future use.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The hybridomas can be grown indefinitely in a suitable cell culture medium.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] They can also be injected into mice (in the peritoneal cavity, surrounding the gut).
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] There, they produce tumors secreting an antibody-rich fluid called ascites fluid.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The medium must be enriched during *in vitro* selection to further favour hybridoma growth.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This can be achieved by the use of a layer of feeder fibrocyte cells or supplement medium such as briclone.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Culture-media conditioned by macrophages can be used.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Production in cell culture is usually preferred as the ascites technique is painful to the animal.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Where alternate techniques exist, ascites is considered unethical.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Several monoclonal antibody technologies have been developed recently, such as phage display, single B cell culture, single cell amplification from various B cell populations and single plasma cell interrogation technologies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Different from traditional hybridoma technology, the newer technologies use molecular biology techniques to amplify the heavy and light chains of the antibody genes by PCR and produce in either bacterial or mammalian systems with recombinant technology.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] One of the advantages of the new technologies is applicable to multiple animals, such as rabbit, llama, chicken and other common experimental animals in the laboratory.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] After obtaining either a media sample of cultured hybridomas or a sample of ascites fluid, the desired antibodies must be extracted.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Cell culture sample contaminants consist primarily of media components such as growth factors, hormones and transferrins.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In contrast, the *in vivo* sample is likely to have host antibodies, proteases, nucleases, nucleic acids and viruses.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In both cases, other secretions by the hybridomas such as cytokines may be present.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] There may also be bacterial contamination and, as a result, endotoxins that are secreted by the bacteria.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Depending on the complexity of the media required in cell culture and thus the contaminants, one or the other method (*in vivo* or *in vitro*) may be preferable.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The sample is first conditioned, or prepared for purification.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Cells, cell debris, lipids, and clotted material are first removed, typically by centrifugation followed by filtration with a 0.45 μm filter.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These large particles can cause a phenomenon called membrane fouling in later purification steps.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In addition, the concentration of product in the sample may not be sufficient, especially in cases where the desired antibody is produced by a low-secreting cell line.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The sample is therefore concentrated by ultrafiltration or dialysis.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Most of the charged impurities are usually anions such as nucleic acids and endotoxins.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These can be separated by ion exchange chromatography.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Either cation exchange chromatography is used at a low enough pH that the desired antibody binds to the column while anions flow through, or anion exchange chromatography is used at a high enough pH that the desired antibody flows through the column while anions bind to it.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Various proteins can also be separated along with the anions based on their isoelectric point (pI).
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In proteins, the isoelectric point (pI) is defined as the pH at which a protein has no net charge.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] When the pH > pI, a protein has a net negative charge, and when the pH < pI, a protein has a net positive charge.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] For example, albumin has a pI of 4.8, which is significantly lower than that of most monoclonal antibodies, which have a pI of 6.1.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Thus, at a pH between 4.8 and 6.1, the average charge of albumin molecules is likely to be more negative, while mAbs molecules are positively charged and hence it is possible to separate them.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Transferrin, on the other hand, has a pI of 5.9, so it cannot be easily separated by this method.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] A difference in pI of at least 1 is necessary for a good separation.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Transferrin can instead be removed by size exclusion chromatography.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] This method is one of the more reliable chromatography techniques.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Since we are dealing with proteins, properties such as charge and affinity are not consistent and vary with pH as molecules are protonated and deprotonated, while size stays relatively constant.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Nonetheless, it has drawbacks such as low resolution, low capacity and low elution times.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] A much quicker, single-step method of separation is protein A/G affinity chromatography.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The antibody selectively binds to protein A/G, so a high level of purity (generally >80%) is obtained.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The generally harsh conditions of this method may damage easily damaged antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] A low pH can break the bonds to remove the antibody from the column.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In addition to possibly affecting the product, low pH can cause protein A/G itself to leak off the column and appear in the eluted sample.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Gentle elution buffer systems that employ high salt concentrations are available to avoid exposing sensitive antibodies to low pH.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Cost is also an important consideration with this method because immobilized protein A/G is a more expensive resin.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] To achieve maximum purity in a single step, affinity purification can be performed, using the antigen to provide specificity for the antibody.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In this method, the antigen used to generate the antibody is covalently attached to an agarose support.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] If the antigen is a peptide, it is commonly synthesized with a terminal cysteine, which allows selective attachment to a carrier protein, such as KLH during development and to support purification.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The antibody-containing medium is then incubated with the immobilized antigen, either in batch or as the antibody is passed through a column, where it selectively binds and can be retained while impurities are washed away.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] An elution with a low pH buffer or a more gentle, high salt elution buffer is then used to recover purified antibody from the support.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Product heterogeneity is common in monoclonal antibodies and other recombinant biological products and is typically introduced either upstream during expression or downstream during manufacturing.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These variants are typically aggregates, deamidation products, glycosylation variants, oxidized amino acid side chains, as well as amino and carboxyl terminal amino acid additions.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These seemingly minute structural changes can affect preclinical stability and process optimization as well as therapeutic product potency, bioavailability and immunogenicity.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The generally accepted purification method of process streams for monoclonal antibodies includes capture of the product target with protein A, elution, acidification to inactivate potential mammalian viruses, followed by ion chromatography, first with anion beads and then with cation beads.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Displacement chromatography has been used to identify and characterize these often unseen variants in quantities that are suitable for subsequent preclinical evaluation regimens such as animal pharmacokinetic studies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Knowledge gained during the preclinical development phase is critical for enhanced product quality understanding and provides a basis for risk management and increased regulatory flexibility.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The recent Food and Drug Administration's Quality by Design initiative attempts to provide guidance on development and to facilitate design of products and processes that maximizes efficacy and safety profile while enhancing product manufacturability.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The production of recombinant monoclonal antibodies involves repertoire cloning, CRISPR/Cas9, or phage display/yeast display technologies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Recombinant antibody engineering involves antibody production by the use of viruses or yeast, rather than mice.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These techniques rely on rapid cloning of immunoglobulin gene segments to create libraries of antibodies with slightly different amino acid sequences from which antibodies with desired specificities can be selected.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The phage antibody libraries are a variant of phage antigen libraries.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These techniques can be used to enhance the specificity with which antibodies recognize antigens, their stability in various environmental conditions, their therapeutic efficacy and their detectability in diagnostic applications.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Fermentation chambers have been used for large scale antibody production.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Recombinant DNA has been explored since the late 1980s to increase residence times.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In one approach called "CDR grafting", mouse DNA encoding the binding portion of a monoclonal antibody was merged with human antibody-producing DNA in living cells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The expression of this "chimeric" or "humanised" DNA through cell culture yielded part-mouse, part-human antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Ever since the discovery that monoclonal antibodies could be generated, scientists have targeted the creation of *fully* human products to reduce the side effects of humanised or chimeric antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Several successful approaches have been proposed: transgenic mice, phage display and single B cell cloning.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies are more expensive to manufacture than small molecules due to the complex processes involved and the general size of the molecules, all in addition to the enormous research and development costs involved in bringing a new chemical entity to patients.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] They are priced to enable manufacturers to recoup the typically large investment costs, and where there are no price controls, such as the United States, prices can be higher if they provide great value.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Once monoclonal antibodies for a given substance have been produced, they can be used to detect the presence of this substance.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Proteins can be detected using the Western blot and immuno dot blot tests.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In immunohistochemistry, monoclonal antibodies can be used to detect antigens in fixed tissue sections, and similarly, immunofluorescence can be used to detect a substance in either frozen tissue section or live cells.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Antibodies can also be used to purify their target compounds from mixtures, using the method of immunoprecipitation.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Therapeutic monoclonal antibodies act through multiple mechanisms, such as blocking of targeted molecule functions, inducing apoptosis in cells which express the target, or by modulating signalling pathways.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] One possible treatment for cancer involves monoclonal antibodies that bind only to cancer-cell-specific antigens and induce an immune response against the target cancer cell.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Such mAbs can be modified for delivery of a toxin, radioisotope, cytokine or other active conjugate or to design bispecific antibodies that can bind with their Fab regions both to target antigen and to a conjugate or effector cell.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Every intact antibody can bind to cell receptors or other proteins with its Fc region.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies used for autoimmune diseases include infliximab and adalimumab, which are effective in rheumatoid arthritis, Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis and ankylosing spondylitis by their ability to bind to and inhibit TNF-α.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Basiliximab and daclizumab inhibit IL-2 on activated T cells and thereby help prevent acute rejection of kidney transplants.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Omalizumab inhibits human immunoglobulin E (IgE) and is useful in treating moderate-to-severe allergic asthma.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies for research applications can be found directly from antibody suppliers, or through use of a specialist search engine like CiteAb.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Below are examples of clinically important monoclonal antibodies.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In 2020, the monoclonal antibody therapies bamlanivimab/etesevimab and casirivimab/imdevimab were given emergency use authorizations by the US Food and Drug Administration to reduce the number of hospitalizations, emergency room visits, and deaths because of COVID-19.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In September 2021, the Biden administration purchased US$2.9 billion worth of Regeneron monoclonal antibodies at $2,100 per dose to curb the shortage.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] As of December 2021, *in vitro* neutralization tests indicate monoclonal antibody therapies (with the exception of sotrovimab and tixagevimab/cilgavimab) were not likely to be active against the Omicron variant.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Over 2021–22, two Cochrane reviews found insufficient evidence for using neutralizing monoclonal antibodies to treat COVID-19 infections.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] The reviews applied only to people who were unvaccinated against COVID‐19, and only to the COVID-19 variants existing during the studies, not to newer variants, such as Omicron.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] In March 2024, pemivibart, a monoclonal antibody drug, received an emergency use authorization from the US FDA for use as pre-exposure prophylaxis to protect certain moderately to severely immunocompromised individuals against COVID-19.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] Several monoclonal antibodies, such as bevacizumab and cetuximab, can cause different kinds of side effects.
[src:antibody-structure/monoclonal-antibody] These side effects can be categorized into common and serious side effects.
